{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492612"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:37:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:37:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1110"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1110"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.01,0.18,0.23,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1110"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116309"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1110"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1110"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98305"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9124"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2556"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34625"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34647"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49914"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116309"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of constant lower abdominal pain associated with loose stools. Her medical history includes hypertension, gout, type 2 diabetes, and a similar episode of abdominal pain two years previously. She takes enalapril, simvastatin, and metformin. She looks well, with a blood pressure of 130/90 mmHg, pulse 90/min, and temperature 38.0\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft, with some tenderness in the left iliac fossa. Her BMI is 29. Her haematological and biochemical values are all within normal limits. HbA1c at her last medical checkup one month ago was 8.5%. A CT scan is ordered and shows thickening of the sigmoid colon and no other abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the strongest indication for admission for her diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The localised tenderness","Her BMI","The temperature","The diabetes","The CT findings"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s lower left quadrant pain, low-grade fever, and typical CT scan findings (eg, thickening of the colonic wall) are consistent with the diagnosis of acute diverticulitis. There is increasing evidence in the literature that many patients with acute diverticulitis can be managed quite satisfactorily at home (antibiotics and out-patient follow-up) and with carefully selected patients only a small proportion will require re-admission. All patients with complicated diverticulitis (eg, perforation, abscess, fistula formation) should receive inpatient management. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIndications for hospitalisation in patients with uncomplicated diverticulitis are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEvidence of one of the following signs of sepsis:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETemp \u0026gt;38 or \u0026lt;36 C\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeart rate \u0026gt;90/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EResp rate \u0026gt;20\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC \u0026gt;12,000/ml or \u0026lt;4000/ml\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECRP \u0026gt;15mg/dL\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESevere abdominal pain or peritonitis and/or failure to control abdominal pain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMicro perforation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAge \u0026gt;70y\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESignificant co-morbidities (e.g. diabetes, recent cardiogenic event, recent decompensated liver failure, chronic steroid use or end stage renal disease)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImmunosuppression\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntolerance of oral intake secondary to bowel obstruction or ileus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-compliance with care / lack of support system / limited home support\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFailed outpatient treatment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients over the age of 65 are more likely to be managed in a hospital, but this is not an absolute indication. In this case, the patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Ediabetes\u003C/strong\u003E and this co-morbidity is a stronger reason than any of the other options to consider the need for in-patient management of her acute diverticulitis. The high level of HbA1c suggests the diabetes is poorly controlled.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Uncomplicated diverticulitis can be managed in an out-patient setting - except where various co-morbidities, such as diabetes, indicate the need for hospitalisation."],"references":["Sartelli M, Weber DG, Kluger Y, et al. 2020 update of the WSES guidelines for the management of acute colonic diverticulitis in the emergency setting. World J Emerg Surg. 2020;15(1):32. doi: 10.1186/s13017-020-00313-4. Available at: https://wjes.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13017-020-00313-4"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98305"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1110"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98305"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T11:21:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T11:22:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1110"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116309"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relati